properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
The Threat is Reduced following the grassfire at Smythes creek. 

  • This Advice message replaces the Watch and Act issued at 3.45pm 7 January 2025.
People located within Bunkers Hill, Haddon, Smythes Creek are now able to resume normal activities.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Emergency services will remain in the area
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby communities and roads. 
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.  

This will be the final message issued for this fire. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service for assistance and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Community Information
properties.webBody:
This message is being issued for Dumosa.

  • There is a building fire at Calder Hwy, Dumosa which is generating a lot of smoke. 
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby roads and communities for up to 48 hours. 
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

Unless the situation changes, this will be the last message issued for this fire.   

Health information: 
  • If you need medical advice for exposure to smoke, seek medical advice or call Nurse on Call on 1300 606 024. 
  • Anyone experiencing wheezing, chest tightness and difficulty breathing should call Triple Zero (000).     
Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.location: areas surrounding the Grampians National Park
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for areas surrounding the Grampians National Park.

  • The bushfire in the Grampians National Park is now contained.
  • This advice message replaces the Advice issued yesterday at 7:15pm. 
  • The threat has subsided and people from areas surrounding the Grampians National Park may resume normal activities. 
  • If returning to the fire affected area, proceed with caution. 
  • Tress affected by bushfire can be extremely dangerous. Do not stand, park or travel in areas of fire affected trees.
Halls Gap and the Grampians National Park remain closed to visitors. No access to the park is permitted. 
  • Fire agencies are planning to reopen Halls Gap to visitors during the week.
  • Planning is also underway for opening parts of the Grampians National Park later in the week. 
  • For details visit the Parks Victoria Website. 

There is currently no threat to communities, but you should continue to stay informed and monitor conditions.

What you should do: 
  • Monitor weather conditions and warnings. Plan for what you would do if the situation changes. 
  • Review your fire survival plan. 
  • If you do not have a plan, decide what you will do if the situation changes.
  • If you see impacted wildlife - Call 1300 356 682. Download the Wildlife Emergency App.
Recovery and Resilience 
If you have been or may be impacted by the current bushfires, it is understandable if you are feeling concerned and experiencing a mix of strong mental, emotional or physical reactions right now. For emergency relief information during major incidents, call the VicEmergency hotline on 1800 226 226 or visit www.emergency.vic.gov.au/relief.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Fire crews will continue to monitor and patrol the fire for several weeks. 
  • You may see smoke and small flare-ups within th burn area which will be dealth with as they arise.
  • Many roads within the fire affected area remain closed. Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/) or call 13 11 70.
  • Smoke from bushfires can reduce air quality and may affect your health. For more information visit the Better Health website. 
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 07/01/2025 06:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#VicFires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

  • There is a haystack fire at Glenloth Rd, Lake Marmal. 
  • This fire may continue to burn for a number of days.
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby roads and communities.
  • Haystack fires are not likely to spread into grassland but do generate a lot of smoke.
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

Unless the situation changes, this will be the last message issued for this fire.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 

  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app.
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires).

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service for assistance and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Advice message is being issued for Bellfield, Bellfield Settlement, Grampians Junction, Halls Gap.

  • The Bushfire in the Grampians National Park is now contained .
  • This advice message replaces the Watch & Act issued 5 January 2025 at 7:00pm. 
  • Residents only are allowed to return to their properties via Traffic Management Points. Proof of address will be required. 
  • If returning to the fire affected area, proceed with caution. 
  • Trees affected by bushfire can be extremely dangerous. Do not stand, park or travel in areas of fire affected trees.
Halls Gap and the Grampians National Park remain closed to visitors. No access to the park is permitted. 
  • Fire agencies are planning to reopen Halls Gap to visitors during the week. 
  • Planning is also underway for opening parts of the Grampians National Park later in the week. 
  • For details visit the Parks Victoria Website.

      • Review your fire survival plan.

      • If you see impacted wildlife - call 1300 226 226 or download the Wildlife Emergency App.

      If you have been or may be impacted by bushfire, it is understandable if you are feeling concerned and experiencing a mix of strong mental, emotional or physical reactions right now. For emergency relief information during major incidents, call the VicEmergency hotline on 1800 226 226 or visit www.emergency.vic.gov.au/relief. 
      Impacts in your area:
